      "target": {
        "kind": "issue",
        "state": "open",
        "locked": false,
        "title": "Preserve structured ACP backend error kinds instead of mapping all errors to `end_turn`",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nIn `src/acp/translator.ts`, ACP events with `state === \"error\"` are currently finished as `end_turn` because the protocol lacks a structured error kind.\n\nThat means timeouts, rate limits, backend crashes, and deliberate refusals are all effectively collapsed into the same client-visible stop reason.\n\n## Why It Matters\n\n- Clients cannot distinguish transient backend failures from normal completion.\n- Retry logic and UX become less accurate.\n- Refusal semantics and operational failures are conflated.\n\n## Suggested Direction\n\nIntroduce or consume a structured error classification such as:\n\n- `refusal`\n- `timeout`\n- `rate_limit`\n- `server_error`\n\nThen map those cases intentionally instead of defaulting all ACP errors to `end_turn`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- ACP translator can preserve backend error class information.\n- Clients can distinguish transient failures from normal end-of-turn behavior.\n- The mapping is covered by targeted tests.\n",
